    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="331"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.20/8–750</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State for
                        Inter-American Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Miller</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-07">August 7,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Some time ago you suggested the preparation of an article on inter-American
                    policy similar to the “X” article.<note n="1" xml:id="d331fn1">Documents in file
                        611.20 indicate that a draft of this article existed at least as early as
                        February 1950.</note> Such an article was prepared by Louis Halle, Planning
                    Adviser in <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>, and was published in the July
                    issue of <hi rend="italic">Foreign Affairs.</hi>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d331fn2">“Y,” “On a Certain Impatience with Latin America,”
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Affairs</hi>, vol. 28, no. 4, (July 1950), pp.
                        565–579.</note> A copy of the magazine is attached and I hope that you will
                    have time to read this excellent restatement of our Latin American policy.</p>
                <p>This policy line has been reflected in three speeches which I have made this
                    year, at the Rotary Club in Charleston, West Virginia last January,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d331fn3">Press Release No. 27, which contains Mr. Miller’s speech of
                        January 11, is included in Department of State <hi rend="italic">Press
                            Releases</hi>, 1950, under date.</note> at the Philadelphia Bulletin
                    Forum on March 22<note n="4" xml:id="d331fn4">“Inter-American Relations in
                        Perspective,” Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, April 3,
                        1950, p. 521.</note> and at the meeting of the Pennsylvania Federation of
                    Labor May 9.<note n="5" xml:id="d331fn5">”The American Way and Standards of
                        Democracy,” <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, May 22, 1950, p. 797.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
